        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>Source flux:

 We evaluated the expected fluxes of CO (J=3-2), 29SiO (J=8-7), and using two-dimensional model images, which were calibrated against previous observations  (Bieging et al. 2000; De Beck et al. 2010; Peng et al. 2013).  

Sensitivity requirement:  

   We require the sensitivity to detect the 29SiO (J=8-7) line at 0.75 arcsec from the star with a  &gt;5-sigma confidence even if 90% of SiO molecules condense into silicate dust (Fig. 2 in Science Justification).  The required sensitivity for the observations with the array configuration of C34-5 and C34-4 results in 2 and 6 mJy/beam, respectively.  We require the same sensitivity of 2 mJy/beam for observations with both configurations.  
   The line emissions of CO, AlOH, and AlO are observed simultaneously with 29SiO.  CO emission is easily detected with this sensitivity.  The sensitivity of 2 mJy enables the detection of AlOH with a 3-sigma confidence if it is present at the same level with the previous single-dish observation at 283.3 GHz (J=9-8) for a red supergiant (Tenenbaum et al. 2010).

Width and required resolution of the spectral lines:

   Previous observations showed that the expansion velocity of the W Hya envelope is about 8 km/s (e.g., Bieging et al. 2000; Peng et al. 2013). We adopt 8 km/s as the line width of 29SiO (J=8-7) and the spectral resolution of 1 km/s is thus required.  We also use the off-line intensity of the 29SiO line to evaluate the continuum emission from the star, which must be subtracted to derive the SiO line intensity in the central region. 

Array configuration:

   The estimated dust forming region of W Hya is at a few Rstar (&lt;0.05 arcsec) from the star (Norris et al. 2012).  It is not possible to resolve the dust formation region with the current ALMA configurations but our goal is to resolve regions including and outside of the dust forming region without significant broadening of the brightness profile close to the star. Based on the distance to the star of 98 pc, the spatial resolution better than 0.25 arcsec is required.  
   The radial profiles of 29SiO line for different degrees of SiO depletion are evaluated by velocity maps from 2D model envelope and simulated observation with CASA. We confirmed that the angular resolution of 0.22 arcsec, which is obtained by the array configuration of C34-5 for band 7, can clearly distinguish whether a large amount of Si remain in gas or condensed as silicates (Fig. 2 in Science Justification).
  The dust shell observed at 18 μm extends to about 2.5 arcsec in radius (Marengo 2000).  In order to obtain the 29SiO flux within the observed dust shell, we require the recoverable scale of 5 arcsec.    
   
Time constraints: 

W Hya is a variable star with a period of 388±5 days (Zhao-Geisler et al. 2011).  The SiO flux outside the dust forming region may not change significantly but observations with the array configurations of C34-4 and C34-5 done within 60 days are preferable. 

“User-defined” calibration: We plan to follow the standard calibration procedures.</prj:justificationText>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
